<Layout
  title="peek vs Sentry Spotlight"
  description="peek vs Sentry Spotlight: peek gives your AI coding agent forensic read access to your real, locally-recorded browser sessions; Spotlight surfaces your Sentry events in-app during development. Different jobs."
>
  <h1>peek vs Sentry Spotlight</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Both put debugging context in front of you locally. The delta: peek records
    your real browser passively and hands the session to your AI coding agent to
    debug what already happened; Spotlight surfaces the events your Sentry SDK
    already emits, in-app, for you to read while you develop.
  </p>

  <p>
    This page is for the person searching &ldquo;Sentry Spotlight alternative&rdquo;
    or &ldquo;local error debugging for an AI agent.&rdquo; No FUD &mdash;
    <a href="https://spotlightjs.com" rel="noopener">Sentry Spotlight</a> is a
    well-built, free, local dev tool. The two overlap on &ldquo;debug locally,&rdquo;
    but they capture different things, for a different consumer. The sections
    below say when each fits.
  </p>

  <h2>At a glance</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th></th>
        <th>peek</th>
        <th>Sentry Spotlight</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Primary consumer</strong></td>
        <td>Your AI coding agent (over MCP)</td>
        <td>You, reading an in-app debug overlay</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>What it captures</strong></td>
        <td>The real browser session itself &mdash; rrweb DOM history, console &amp; network errors, the action before an error</td>
        <td>The events your Sentry SDK emits (errors, traces, spans)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Instrumentation</strong></td>
        <td>None &mdash; a browser extension records passively; no SDK in your app</td>
        <td>Requires the Sentry SDK wired into your app</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Output</strong></td>
        <td>Forensic answers to your agent + a runnable Playwright repro</td>
        <td>A live, readable view of Sentry events during dev</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Data location</strong></td>
        <td>Local: <code>~/.peek/sessions.db</code>. Nothing leaves your machine to a vendor.</td>
        <td>Local during dev; the same events also flow to Sentry if configured</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>License</strong></td>
        <td>Apache-2.0, OSS</td>
        <td>MIT, OSS</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>When Sentry Spotlight is the right choice</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>You already run the Sentry SDK and want its events surfaced in-app while you develop.</li>
    <li>You want errors, traces, and spans correlated the way Sentry models them.</li>
    <li>Your debugging is you-reading-events, not an AI agent querying a session.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When peek is the right choice</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>You want your AI coding agent to debug a real browser session &mdash; &ldquo;what did the user do right before this error?&rdquo; &mdash; without instrumenting your app.</li>
    <li>You want the session turned into a runnable Playwright repro the agent can re-run to verify its fix.</li>
    <li>You want capture to stay local with no SDK and no vendor account.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Can you use both?</h2>
  <p>
    Yes &mdash; they sit at different layers. Spotlight shows you the Sentry events
    your app emits; peek gives your agent the surrounding browser session to
    reconstruct how the error was reached and to produce a repro. One is for
    you, one is for your agent.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this page exists</h2>
  <p>
    peek is often mis-filed next to anything labeled &ldquo;local debugging.&rdquo;
    It isn&apos;t an error-monitoring overlay &mdash; it&apos;s forensic read access to
    your real, passively-recorded browser sessions, built for an AI coding agent.
    This page draws that line honestly.
  </p>

  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
    Found something inaccurate above? Open a PR on
